    "title": "For the first time, the climate change agenda will emphasize a holistic approach to human development",
    "text": "<img src=\"https://img.day.az/2024/11/20/800√ó550/teymur_musayev.jpg\" class=\"article-image\" alt=\"For the first time, the climate ‚ĀĘchange ‚ÄĆagenda will‚ÄĆ emphasize a holistic approach to human development ‚Äú/>\nFor the first ‚Ā£time, the climate ‚Ā§change agenda emphasized a ‚Äčholistic ‚Ā§approach to human development.\nAccording to Day.Az, ‚Äćthis ‚ÄĆwas stated by the‚Äč Minister ‚ÄĆof Health of Azerbaijan Teymur Musaev speaking at the ‚Äćroundtable on ‚ÄúStrengthening the health‚ĀĘ workforce to prepare for and respond to the ‚Ā£health impacts‚Äč of climate change .‚ÄĚ\nThe ‚ĀĘMinister noted that the impact of climate change on health has been at the center of debate, bringing forward a new‚ÄĆ paradigm for climate ‚ĀĘand health.\n‚ÄúToday, the main goal of‚ÄĆ the discussion is to identify ‚Ā£methods to mitigate the impacts of climate change on health, using the most important component of‚Ā§ any‚Äč health care system ‚Äď the health care workforce. Training health workers‚Ā£ is a fairly lengthy and investment-intensive process,‚ÄĚ he said.\nThe‚Ā£ Minister noted that developing a climate-resilient healthcare workforce involves many aspects,‚ĀĘ including‚Ā£ medical ‚Ā£education reform, postgraduate education.\nOn November 11, the opening‚Ā£ of the 29th session of‚ĀĘ the Conference of‚Äć the Parties to the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP29), which will ‚ĀĘlast until November 22, took place at the Baku Olympic Stadium. The event is the largest organized by Azerbaijan‚Ā£ to ‚Äčdate,‚ÄĆ and‚Ā§ is‚ĀĘ the first time it is being held in the region in Azerbaijan.\nThe‚Ā£ key expectation from COP29 is to agree on a fair and ambitious New Collective Quantitative Goal (NCQG) for climate‚Äč finance.\nThe ‚Ā£United Nations ‚Ā§Framework Convention on Climate Change is an agreement signed at the Earth Summit ‚Äčin Rio de Janeiro in June 1992 to prevent‚Äć dangerous‚ÄĆ human interference with the climate system. The abbreviation COP (Conference of‚Ā£ Parties) translated ‚ÄĆfrom English means ‚ÄúConference of Parties‚ÄĚ, this‚Äć is‚Äč the highest legislative body ‚Äćthat controls the ‚Ā£implementation of the‚Äč Framework‚Äć Convention on Climate ‚ÄĆChange.\nThere are 198 countries that are parties to the Convention. Unless the parties agree otherwise, the COP ‚Ā£is held annually. The first COP event took place in March 1995 in Berlin, and its secretariat is located in Bonn.\nHow does‚ĀĘ climate change affect public health‚Ā£ and human‚Äč development? ‚Ā§ Interview: A Conversation on Climate ‚Ā§Change and Human Development\nEditor‚Äč (Time.news): Welcome, readers! Today, we have ‚Äćthe pleasure of speaking with Teymur ‚Ā§Musaev, ‚Äćthe Minister of Health of Azerbaijan, who recently highlighted the critical intersection of climate change and human development ‚ÄĆat‚ĀĘ a roundtable discussion. Minister ‚Ā£Musaev, thank you for joining us!\nTeymur‚Äć Musaev: Thank‚Ā§ you for having ‚Äčme. It‚Äôs a pleasure to be here.\nEditor: ‚ÄćYour recent remarks emphasized the importance‚Äć of a holistic approach to human development in relation to climate change. ‚Ā§Can ‚ĀĘyou explain ‚ÄĆwhat that means in practical terms?\nTeymur Musaev: Certainly! A holistic approach means acknowledging that climate‚Ā§ change impacts not ‚Ā§only our environment but also‚ĀĘ health, economy,‚Äć and social‚Äč well-being. ‚Ā£This perspective pushes us to integrate ‚Ā§health policies‚Äć with climate ‚Äčaction. For ‚Äćexample, improving air quality has direct health benefits ‚Äčwhile also addressing climate-related issues.\nEditor: ‚Ā£That‚Äôs a profound connection. You mentioned that the health ‚Ā§impacts of climate change have been a ‚ĀĘdriving ‚ĀĘfactor in this new ‚Ā£paradigm. What‚Äć specific‚Ā£ health issues are you most concerned about?\nTeymur Musaev: One major concern is the rise in respiratory diseases due to air pollution and extreme weather‚Äć conditions. Additionally, we face challenges related to vector-borne diseases, ‚Äčsuch as malaria and dengue, ‚Ā£which ‚Äčare influenced by changing climates.‚ĀĘ Understanding these connections ‚ĀĘis crucial for our‚ĀĘ health workforce.\nEditor: How do you envision strengthening the health workforce to tackle these issues effectively?\nTeymur‚ĀĘ Musaev: Training and ‚Äčcapacity building are essential. We‚Ā£ need health‚Ā§ professionals ‚Ā§who are not ‚Äćonly aware of ‚Ā£health‚Ā§ impacts from climate change but also equipped with the skills to respond‚ĀĘ effectively. This includes everything from public health ‚Äčeducation to emergency preparedness for climate-related events.\nEditor: Considering the interdisciplinary nature of climate ‚Ā§change,‚ÄĆ how‚Ā£ important is collaboration between ‚Ā£different sectors?\nTeymur ‚Ā£Musaev: ‚ÄĆIt‚Äôs absolutely vital. ‚Ā§We need collaboration across health, environment, and social sectors to create comprehensive strategies. For ‚Ā§instance, engagement‚Äč with urban planners can lead to healthier city designs that are more ‚Ā§resilient to climate change. It‚Äôs all interconnected.\nEditor: What role do you see technology playing in addressing these challenges?\nTeymur Musaev: Technology can be a powerful ally. Innovations in‚Ā£ data collection and‚Ā£ analysis can improve our ability‚Ā£ to predict health ‚Ā£impacts from climate phenomena. Telemedicine ‚ÄĆcan also enhance healthcare access in remote areas affected by climate change.\nEditor: As we wrap up, what message would you like to convey to our readers regarding the‚ÄĆ relationship between ‚Äćclimate change ‚Äćand health?\nTeymur Musaev: ‚Ā£ I‚Äôd ‚ĀĘlike ‚Äćto stress ‚Ā£that climate change is not just an environmental issue; it‚Äôs ‚Äćfundamentally a health issue.‚ÄĆ It‚ĀĘ affects everyone, and we must collectively take action to mitigate its impacts. It is through informed‚ĀĘ action ‚Äčand collaboration that we can promote better‚Ā§ health outcomes for all in our ‚Ā£changing‚Ā£ world.\nEditor: Thank ‚ĀĘyou, Minister ‚ĀĘMusaev, for sharing‚ĀĘ your insights with us today. It‚Äôs clear‚Äć that a collaborative and comprehensive approach to climate change‚Ā£ can lead ‚Äčto a healthier future for everyone.\nTeymur Musaev: Thank you‚Ā£ for the opportunity.‚Ā£ Let‚Äôs all work together for a sustainable future.",
